1. Tech Stack & Architecture
Core stack
Framework: Next.js (App Router, React Server Components first).
Language: TypeScript (no any except in well-documented escape hatches).
Styling: Tailwind CSS + Shadcn UI (Radix primitives).
State/Data: TanStack Query for remote data, Zustand for client global UI state.
Validation: Zod for all user input, query params, and API responses.
Architecture
RSC first: Prefer server components for all data-fetching views.
Client components: Only for interaction (maps, charts, sliders, drag-and-drop, etc.).
Feature-based structure:
app/(marketing)/...
app/(dashboard)/...
components/weather-current/, components/weather-forecast/, components/location-picker/, etc.
lib/api/, lib/weather/, lib/validation/, lib/ui/, etc.
types/ for shared domain types (weather, locations, alerts, preferences).
2. Naming, Structure, and File Organization
Directories
Use kebab-case for folders: components/current-conditions, features/location-search.
Files
Component files in components/ or feature folders:
Top-level export is the main component.
Group subcomponents and helpers in the same file if small; otherwise create *-subcomponent.tsx or helpers.ts.
Naming
Booleans: isLoading, hasError, shouldRefresh, isSevereWeather.
Async functions: fetchWeatherByCoords, loadUserPreferences, getForecastSummary.
Domain clarity: Prefer hourlyForecast, dailyForecast, uvIndex over generic names.
3. Data Fetching, Caching, and Weather Domain Rules
Server data fetching
Use Next.js RSC data functions (async server components, getX helpers in lib/weather/) for primary weather data:
getCurrentConditions(location: LocationInput)
getHourlyForecast(location: LocationInput)
getDailyForecast(location: LocationInput)
getWeatherAlerts(location: LocationInput)
Centralize API calls in lib/api/weather-client.ts with:
Strongly typed responses.
Zod validation of external API data.
Consistent error mapping (see custom error types below).
Caching
Use fetch with Next.js caching options and/or revalidate for predictable fresh intervals:
Current conditions: revalidate: 60 (or configurable).
Hourly: revalidate: 5 * 60.
Daily: revalidate: 30 * 60.
For client data (progressive enhancement, refetch-on-focus): use TanStack Query with stable keys:
['weather', 'current', locationKey]
['weather', 'hourly', locationKey]
['weather', 'alerts', locationKey]
Location handling
Normalize location into a Location type (e.g. city, lat, lon, country, timezone).
Derive timezone-aware timestamps on the server using a dedicated utility (lib/weather/time.ts).
4. State Management Guidelines
Global state (Zustand)
Use for UI concerns and user preferences, not core weather data:
Selected location.
Temperature unit (C/F), wind speed units, theme (light/dark/system).
Visible panels (e.g. radar vs forecast, chart toggles).
No API calls inside Zustand stores. Instead:
Read/write preferences.
Let components use TanStack Query for network data.
Local state
Prefer useState and useReducer for local UI-only state in client components.
Avoid “global everything” – scope state to the smallest useful context.
5. Client vs Server Components
Default: Server Component
Pages showing weather data but with simple interaction (<Link> navigation, simple filters passed via URL) stay on the server.
Use URL searchParams or segment config for filters (units, language, view).
Client Component only when needed
Interactions requiring real-time updates, browser APIs, or complex transitions:
Geolocation access.
Dragable map / radar.
Interactive charts (zoom/hover).
Client-side search/autocomplete for locations.
In client components:
Keep them small and focused.
Prefer hooks for complex behavior: useLocationSearch, useRadarInteraction.
6. Performance and Optimization
Dynamic imports
Use next/dynamic for heavy/rarely-used UI:
Charts, radar maps, 3D visualizations, advanced analytics.
Example: const WeatherRadar = dynamic(() => import('@/components/weather-radar'), { ssr: false, loading: SkeletonRadar }).
Images
Use next/image with:
WebP-first where possible.
Explicit width/height and sizes.
placeholder="blur" for hero images; loading="lazy" for below-the-fold content.
Bundle hygiene
Avoid importing large libs into RSC and client components unnecessarily.
Share pure helpers via lib/ (pure TS) instead of re-implementing logic.
Rendering
Memoize expensive client subtrees (React.memo, useMemo, useCallback) but only when profiling shows benefit.
Co-locate expensive computations in RSC or on the server.
7. Error Handling, Validation, and Custom Errors
Zod schemas
All external inputs must be validated:
Weather API responses.
Query params: location, units, language.
User settings forms, feedback, alerts configuration.
Store schemas in lib/validation/ and reuse across server and client.
Custom errors
Use domain-specific error types in lib/errors.ts:
WeatherApiError
LocationValidationError
RateLimitError
UnexpectedWeatherDataError
Ensure each has:
name, message, optional code, and optional cause.
Guard clauses / early returns
Always validate preconditions at the top of a function (if (!location) return ...).
Fail fast where input or environment is invalid.
User-facing error UX
Use shared components for errors and empty states, e.g.:
ErrorState
EmptyState
RetryBanner
Map technical errors to user-friendly messages with safe detail.
8. UI/UX and Design System
Design system
Use Shadcn UI components as base primitives and wrap into weather-specific components when they repeat:
WeatherCard, MetricBadge, AlertTag, TimelineRow.
Whenever markup repeats between pages, refactor into shared components before closing the task (your own rule).
Responsiveness
Mobile-first Tailwind: flex, grid, gap, space-y-*.
Ensure critical weather info (current conditions, alerts) is immediately visible on small screens.
Accessibility
Use Radix primitives where appropriate for focus management.
Add semantic roles and ARIA for interactive charts and maps when needed (e.g., summary text for screen readers).
Dark mode
Support system-dark-mode with a toggle using Shadcn theme helpers and Tailwind classes.
9. Security & Reliability
Secrets
Weather API keys, geocoding keys, and analytics keys must live in .env or platform secrets; never committed.
Input safety
Sanitize all text inputs that may appear in UI or logs.
Rate-limit high-frequency operations (location search, geolocation-based refresh) on the server.
Network robustness
Timeouts and retries for weather API calls with backoff (e.g. using AbortController or fetch wrappers).
Graceful degradation when an API is unavailable:
Fallback to cached data when available.
Clear, non-blocking messaging to the user.
10. Testing Strategy
Unit tests
Use Jest + React Testing Library.
Focus on:
Domain logic (lib/weather/ – temperature conversion, feels-like, condition classification).
Validation schemas (lib/validation/ – query params, API responses).
Components with nontrivial logic (derived states, edge cases, severe weather).
Integration tests
For critical flows (e.g. “search city → see current + hourly forecast + alerts”).
Naming & structure
Tests colocated as *.test.ts / *.test.tsx.
Use descriptive test names and minimal mocking of external APIs.
Temporary tests
If you create throwaway/test files for investigation, delete them once no longer needed (per your rule).
11. Documentation & Comments
Component documentation
Use minimal but clear JSDoc for exported hooks, helpers, and critical components:
What the function does.
What inputs/outputs are (especially around weather domain).
Any non-obvious assumptions (timezones, units, fallback strategy).
Complex logic only
Only comment when the logic is non-trivial (e.g., computing storm severity index, merging multiple API sources).
Do not narrate obvious code.
12. Working Methodology for New Features
When implementing or refactoring a feature (e.g. new “Air Quality” panel, “Storm Tracker”, “Feels Like” timeline):

Analysis
Identify required data (from weather API or separate service), validation schemas, and new domain types.
Plan
Sketch the RSC entry point, client subcomponents, and required hooks/helpers.
Implement
Start from lib/api + lib/validation + types.
Create or extend RSC page/segment.
Add minimal client components as needed (charts, radar, etc.) using dynamic import.
Review & Optimize
Check for duplication and refactor into shared components.
Check bundle size impact (avoid unnecessary client imports).
Confirm Zod schemas and error handling paths.
Test & Document
Add/extend unit tests.
Add/adjust JSDoc and any non-obvious comments.
